<F P=100> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tibet Chairman on Struggle Against `Separatists' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tibet Chairman on Struggle Against `Separatists' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2806031794 Hong Kong WEN WEI PO in Chinese 27 Jun 94 p a2 </F>
<F P=103> HK2806031794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong WEN WEI PO </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by staff reporter Yang Yung-nian (2799 3057 1628) </F>
stationed in Southwest China: "Tibet Further Stabilizes 
Situation, Determined To Deal With Separatists According to Law"] 
  [Text] Lhasa, 26 Jun (WEN WEI PO) -- In an exclusive 
interview with this reporter in Lhasa a few days ago, Gyaincain 
Norbu, chairman of the Tibet Autonomous Regional People's 
Government, pointed out: "The situation in Tibet has been 
further stabilized, national unity has been further solidified, 
and public security has further improved." 
  While expressing profound confidence in the struggle against 
Tibetan separatists, Gyaincain Norbu emphatically pointed out 
the necessity of maintaining vigilance amid the atmosphere of 
optimism. He said: "The struggle between separatists and 
antiseparatists in the region is a protracted, acute, and 
complicated one." The regional government leader went on to 
explain: "With the support of the international anti-Chinese 
forces, the Dalai clique took advantage of some social hot spots 
in the hinterland, such as the problems of commodity prices and 
taxation, to try its utmost to disrupt unity and stability and 
obstruct reform and development in Tibet." He added: 
"Certainly, we maintain a high degree of vigilance. Whether 
the separatists, particularly the plotters behind the scenes, 
take advantage of the hot spots in society or directly flaunt 
the banner of `Tibet independence,' we will adopt resolute and 
decisive measures to deal with them according to the law." 
  Recently, when interviewed by this reporter on another 
occasion, Tudeng, head of the Public Health Department of the 
Tibet Autonomous Region, said that the period between 1997 and 
2000 will see a baby boom in Tibet, so it is anticipated that 
the population of Tibet will exceed 2.5 million by the year 
2000. The birth rate in Tibet last year was 23.4 per thousand, 
and allowing for the number of deaths, the natural growth rate 
was 15.6 per thousand, while the natural growth rate across the 
country during the same period was approximately 11 per 
thousand. By the end of last year, there were some 2.2 million 
people in the entire region, a net increase of 36,000 people 
over 1992, and more than double as compared with the population 
in the 1950's. The average life-span of Tibetans has also 
increased to 65 from 36 in the 1950's. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

