<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sources Say Consumer Imports To Hit `All-Time High' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sources Say Consumer Imports To Hit `All-Time High' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2706142394 Taipei CNA in English 1346 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2706142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y.C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 27 (CNA) -- Taiwan's bid to join the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, or GATT, is expected to 
push up imports of consumer goods to an all-time high, trade 
sources said Monday [27 Jun]. 
  The sources forecast that imports of consumer products will 
reach U.S.$11 billion this year, mostly attributable to relaxed 
tariff restrictions. 
  They said further import-duty reductions are a must if 
Taiwan 
expects to gain membership in the Geneva-based world trade 
regulating body by the end of the year. Taiwan now has observer 
status with GATT. 
  With lower tariffs, they pointed out, a substantial increase 
in imports, epecially of consumer products, is almost a 
certainty. When the government slashed import duties in 1988 and 
1992, imports of consumer goods jumped 64.2 percent and 35.7 
percent to U.S.$5.68 billion and U.S.$9.27 billion, 
respectively, they said. 
  Government statistics show that consumer imports totaled 
U.S.$4.65 billion in the first five months of the year, 
accounting for 13.6 percent of Taiwan's aggregate imports and an 
increase of 1.8 percent from the year-earlier level. 
  The officials attributed the growth to the tariff reductions 
that occurred earlier this year, when import duties on 70 items 
were cut. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

