<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister, U.S. Officials, Discuss Crime Fighting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister, U.S. Officials, Discuss Crime Fighting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2806075094 Taipei CNA in English 0722 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2806075094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bill Wang] </F>
  [Text] Washington, June 27 (CNA) -- Justice Minister Ma 
Ying-jeou of the Republic of China [ROC] Monday [27 Jun] met 
with U.S. officials in Washington to discuss joint 
crime-fighting efforts. 
  Ma, the first ROC justice minister to visit the U.S. capital 
since the two countries severed diplomatic ties in 1979, said 
that he met with U.S. officials from the Justice Department and 
the State Department on proposed mutual legal assistance and 
extradition treaties. 
  The minister said that there is a growing consensus between 
the two sides on the need for such agreements. Ma said that 
some 157 suspects wanted by authorities in Taiwan are either in 
the United States or are believed to be here but cannot be 
brought to justice because there is no extradition treaty 
between the two sides. 
  Ma added that Washington has signed mutual legal assistance 
treaties with 15 different countries and is interested in 
signing a similar agreement with Taipei. 
  Meanwhile, Ma met with officials from the Drug Enforcement 
Agency, the Bureau of Prisons, and the Government Ethics Office 
to discuss anti-drug efforts, prison administration and the 
enforcement of government ethics. 
  Drug use is becoming a sejious problem in Taiwan, Ma told 
the 
officials. In 1933, law enforcement agents in Taiwan seized 
1,110 kilograms of heroin, morphine and marijuana and 3,357 
kilograms of amphetamine, up 133 percent and 17 percent 
respectively from the previous year, he said. 
  He also refuted a State Department report released earlier 
this year which claimed Taiwan is an international drug transit 
point. 
  Ma arrived in the United States last week to attend the 
convention of the National Association of State Attorneys 
General in San Antonio, Texas. He came to Washington Saturday 
and is scheduled to leave here for home Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

