<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-125 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Northeast Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Good Harvest' Expected in Northeast Provinces </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Good Harvest' Expected in Northeast Provinces </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2806144794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1433 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2806144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Harbin, June 28 (XINHUA) -- Northeast China, known 
as the country's largest bread basket, is expected to reap 
another good harvest as major crops like maize, soybean, rice, 
Chinese sorghum, millet and beets are all growing well. 
  Maize makes up one-third of the grain production in the 
three 
northeast provinces of Heilongjiang, Jilin and Liaoning, which 
are growing 5.7 million hectares of maize this year. 
  Sown areas for major crops like maize and soybean have 
largely been expanded this year as farmers have been encouraged 
by price incentives and various preferential measures by central 
and local governments. 
  An average northeastern Chinese farmer has 0.27 hectares of 
arable land, well above the national average. The three 
provinces have turned out over 50 billion kg since 1990. The 
region's grain output reached a record high of 60 billion kg 
last year, 25 billion kg of which were sold to the state, making 
the region a major bread basket in China. 

</TEXT>

